metadata.name: Take Wing #52
metadata.description:
“Take Wing” is a generative art collection depicting the hope, optimism, and thrilling excitement of a person taking off, gaining traction, and soaring to new heights and off into the great unknown.  

The algorithm behind the piece stems from an attempt to go back to art fundamentals and codify composition rules and painterly techniques into a generative form - taking into account focal points, contrast, eye movement, and color theory while still giving the algorithm freedom to explore random color palettes, random flow field movement, random brush strokes, and many other degrees of freedom.

The collection is made in pure code with p5.js and a few GLSL fragment shaders.

The piece has been created to be exhibited at "In Touch" with VerticalCryptoArt in Berlin in September 2022, curated by Anika Meier.

------------------------------------------------

To get a (somewhat) high-resolution output, open the live view of your token, and then edit the URL adding &h=5400 at the end of it.  5400 is the tallest you can go, but you can also put a smaller number if you desire.  Be aware that this will only work on a machine with a very beefy GPU, and even then may take a bit, so please be patient!

metadata.name: Part:Counterpart #247
metadata.description:
'Part:Counterpart' is an experiment in form, disintegration, and context. Each work is created within one of three modes, Part, Counterpart, or Part:Counterpart.

In experimenting, I've enjoyed taking a simple composition and breaking it down with various methods. This transforms the original composition into something new, but it also begins to lose what the original had to say. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, and I want to dive a little deeper and explore ideas as a sort of tangible substance. Already we're comparing ideas against their translations and evolutions, but what happens if we present them both within the context of the other?

Additionally, what if we present both of these ideas with echoes and tangents, discussion around the ideas and their practical applications instead of imagined? Sure, these aren't our idea, or even our translation, but they exist only because the originals do.

How does this change our opinion of the original? Is every idea destined to be picked apart and reimagined forever until it bears only a faint resemblance? Where is the line between our Counterpart and an echo?

This piece hopes to inspire contemplation on the nature of storytelling and artistic inspiration.

10% of ideas are encrypted to obscure the original Part.
Press ’s’ to save a 3600x4500 png.
Press ‘p’ to save the original Part, pure and untouched.

metadata.name: Alleles #175
metadata.description:
An allele, short for 'allelomorph', is an alternative version of a specific gene.

This collection (which is in no way scientifically accurate), was born out of an exercise in simplicity. Outputs are made up of arrangements of squares in various compositions, yet within that we are free to imagine what they could mean. For some, the resulting shapes might represent DNA strands or atoms. Others might see cells or the building blocks of the hereditary instructions that shape us as individuals. 

A generative genetic report accompanies each output to spark the imagination and attempt to attach further meaning to each composition. Some gene sequences carry mutations, however not all mutations are visually apparent. Please refer to the fxhash features to view the reports accordingly.

Texture is used subtly, so for maximum enjoyment it is recommended that you save and view your outputs at full size in order to best enjoy the details.

Press 'S' to save a 2400 x 3396 px PNG file.

metadata.name: Plottable Memories: Train Station #146
metadata.description:
'Memories: Train Station' explores plottable abstract photography composition around the "Train Station" theme. Memories can be blurry, faded and abstract and the strokes texturing aim to reflect that.

Many images are used as primitive to make the plot texture. The work is very generative and have great range of variety thanks to the many effects combined together. Photos has been taken by @greweb in Paris' "Gare de l'Est" train station.

Traits of the art includes a suggested "Title" that is self-generated.

PLOTTABLE?!

A SVG file can be exported (right click save) to plot the piece physically. The plot is made of up to 200 000 points – making it time consuming to produce. It is recommended to optimize the pen travel. Inks can have surprising outcomes when done physically.

The digital NFT is the recipe to a plottable art piece, owning it confers the right to plot or request a physical plot from @greweb (https://greweb.me/plots/nft). @greweb would use fountain pens but other plotting artists are free to achieve it with their own materials and ship to collectors – as long as NFT is owned at request time.

More details and Source code: https://github.com/gre/gre/tree/master/doodles/plottable-memories-train-station

@greweb – 2022 – tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM – CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

metadata.name: Women in art #39
metadata.description:
According to Women Can't Paint, a book by Helen Gorrill, paintings made by men sell for 10x as much as women's paintings.

This piece is one of two conceptual generative artworks. One is called "Men in art", the other "Women in art". They are identical except for two differences:
1. The dithering filter in "Men in art" favors blue colors over red ones, while "Women in art" do the opposite.
2. The price of "Men in art" is 10 tez, while "Women in art" is priced at 1 tez.

Made with p5.js, Typescript and Fettepalette.

There is a secret key, which removes the dithering filter.

metadata.name: River Prairie #37
"Alphabetic ancestral signs" - (Matrix v3) #54
metadata.description:
The "Alphabetic Signs" series finds its roots in different places: in my physical work, in a study on letters and typefaces, but also in graffiti and street art.

In this project I was inspired by the symbols of the ancestors. 
Prehistoric signs found in caves and hieroglyphs from different eras, such as the Inca or the Sumerian ones.
I wrote the Javascript code to compose 31 different ancestral signs that were used to fill a pseudo-random matrix.

Each element is coded to adapt to different areas on the canvas, tightening, stretching and expanding.

This work uses p5.js library.

metadata.name: reborn #60
metadata.description:
This is an album of cities too ideal to ever materialise.

It consists of 256 algorithmically generated plans that resemble drawings of Vincenzo Scamozzi, Pietro Cataneo, Filarete and other theorists of the Italian Renaissance. The cities differ in size, the grid of the streets, the landscape around them and the people that inhabit their utopian walls. They carry names that are Italian exonyms of real European cities, drawing a vision of a different world that enacts a mixture of military perfection with social superiority. Flawless, harmonious, unconquerable and utterly impossible.

History brought us many theories about ideal cities, but very few examples exist today. Italian Palmanova or Polish Zamość are the few to remind us how hard it is to shape reality according to ideals. When confronted with the material world, its idealism becomes the city's grates foe.

To zoom, press a mouse button over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

metadata.name: Obliques #59
metadata.description:
Obliques are a reinterpretation of Parallels, a collection of AI generated color fields by Marc Maurer. Many of the pieces in that collection are CC0, which basically means they can be reused for other projects, like this one.

Obliques takes artifacts from Parallels and uses them as brushes, painting slices of the original image on the canvas in a (hopefully) pleasant, chaotic way.

About 10% will be "Glitched".

The "Source Material" property will tell you the name of piece that it is using.

You can see Marc Maurer's Parallels project here:
https://objkt.com/collection/KT1TiSEcASGD19SW8bmqrqgSgCBkwXqDdTJ1

Obliques are also CC0, so feel free use anything here in other projects.

You can read more about CC0 here:
https://creativecommons.org/share-your-work/public-domain/cc0/

G : Toggle Grain
M : Toggle Matte
S : Save Image
1 -> 6 : Set pixel density
(Default pixel density is 1 @ 2000x2000)
